SIMPLE: fluke
RECORDS: 3

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Fluke
<hw>Fluke</hw> <pr>(fl⟦umac⟧k <it>or</it> fl⟦oomac⟧k)</pr>,
<pos>n.</pos> <ety>[Cf. AS. <ets>fl⟦omac⟧c</ets> a kind of flatfish,
Icel. <ets>fl⟦omac⟧ki</ets> a kind of halibut.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn>
<fld>(Zool.)</fld> <def>The European flounder. See
<er>Flounder</er>.</def> <altsp>[Written also <asp>fleuk</asp>,
<asp>flook</asp>, and <asp>flowk</asp>.]</altsp>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <fld>(Zool.)</fld> <def>Any American flounder of the
genus <gen>Paralichthys</gen>, especially <spn>Paralicthys
dentatus</spn>, found in the Atlantic Ocean and in adjacent bays.</def>
<au>RHUD</au>⟦br⟧
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <fld>(Zool.)</fld> <def>A parasitic trematode worm of
several species, having a flat, lanceolate body and two suckers. Two
species (<spn>Fasciola hepatica</spn> and <spn>Distoma
lanceolatum</spn>) are found in the livers of sheep, and produce the
disease called <causes>rot</causes>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><-- p. 575 --></p>

<p><ent>Fluke</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Fluke
<hw>Fluke</hw> <pr>(fl⟦umac⟧k)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[Cf. LG.
<ets>flunk</ets>, <ets>flunka</ets> wing, the palm of an anchor; perh.
akin to E. <ets>fly</ets>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>The part of an anchor
which fastens in the ground; a flook. See <er>Anchor</er>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <fld>(Zool.)</fld> <def>One of the lobes of a whale's
tail, so called from the resemblance to the fluke of an
anchor.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>An instrument for cleaning out a hole drilled in
stone for blasting.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>An accidental and favorable stroke at billiards
(called a <xex>scratch</xex> in the United States); hence, any
accidental or unexpected advantage; <as>as, he won by a
<ex>fluke</ex></as>.</def> <mark>[Cant, Eng.]</mark> <rj><au>A.
Trollope.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Fluke</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 3 ====
HEADWORD: Fluke
<hw>Fluke</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. t. & i.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. &
p. p.</pos> <conjf>Fluked</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb.
n.</pos> <conjf>Fluking</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>.]</vmorph> <def>To get or
score by a fluke; <as>as, to <ex>fluke</ex> a play in
billiards</as>.</def> <mark>[Slang]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>Webster 1913 Suppl.</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Flukeworm</ent>⟦br⟧
